Implementation Notes

Start with Screen 1 (Integrations page) — it's the entry point and the simplest screen. Get the card layout and connect/disconnect flow working first.
Provider logos — copy SVG code from prototype GitHub repo (components/integrations/ProviderLogo.tsx). Convert React JSX to Vue template syntax. Or extract SVGs into separate .svg files in assets/icons/providers/.
QToggle iOS style — Quasar's default toggle looks different from iOS. Apply custom CSS:

css.ios-toggle .q-toggle__inner {
  width: 51px;
  height: 31px;
}
.ios-toggle .q-toggle__thumb {
  width: 27px;
  height: 27px;
}

Gradient bar on connected cards — use CSS pseudo-element:

css.provider-card--connected::before {
  content: '';
  position: absolute;
  top: 0; left: 0; right: 0;
  height: 3px;
  background: linear-gradient(90deg, var(--brand-color), #16A34A);
  border-radius: 16px 16px 0 0;
}

Card hover effects — use CSS transitions:

css.provider-card {
  transition: transform 200ms ease, box-shadow 200ms ease, border-color 200ms ease;
}
.provider-card:hover {
  transform: translateY(-2px);
  box-shadow: 0 8px 24px rgba(0,0,0,0.08), 0 0 0 1px rgba(0,102,255,0.1);
}

Page transitions — use Vue's <Transition> component or Quasar's built-in page transitions.
Toast notifications — use $q.notify() with position 'bottom-right' and 3000ms timeout.
Until backend is ready — use mock data (same as prototype). The Pinia store actions should return mock data with a simulated delay (await new Promise(r => setTimeout(r, 500))). When backend endpoints are available, replace mock calls with actual API calls.


